Period analysis has been shown to provide more up-to-date estimates of long-term 
cancer survival rates than traditional cohort-based analysis. Here, we provide 
detailed period estimates of 5- and 10-year relative survival by cancer site, 
country, sex and age for calendar years 2000-2002. In addition, pan-European 
estimates of 1-, 5- and 10-year relative survival are provided. Overall, 
survival estimates were mostly higher than previously available cohort 
estimates. For most cancer sites, survival in countries from Northern Europe, 
Central Europe and Southern Europe was substantially higher than in the United 
Kingdom and Ireland and in countries from Eastern Europe. Furthermore, relative 
survival was also better in female than in male patients and decreased with age 
for most cancer sites.

